/*E*/
/*S*/ Startbeschreibung
@node "Startdescription" "2. FreshIconizer - Startdescription"
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{b}@{u}2. Startdescription@{uu}@{ub}@{FG TEXT}
FreshIconizer can be started either from your Shell or from Workbench by  a
double-click on its icon.

After the start, FreshIconizer opens its @{"GUI" LINK "Usage"}.

While startup of FreshIconizer a settings-file is loaded out of the "ENV:".
If this file can't be found default settings are used.
@endnode
/*E*/
/*S*/ Eigenschaften
@node "Features" "FreshIconizer - Features"
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{b}@{u}3. Features@{uu}@{ub}@{FG TEXT}
@{i}Here the features of FreshIconizer shall be named and common problems shall
be told.@{ui}

FreshIconizer is a Commodity and though it can  be  displayed  and  managed
with the Exchange-tool.

'Cause FreshIconizers' GUI uses (requires) the intuition-add  on  MUI,  its
possible  to  configure the GUI through the MUI preferences program. Please
note, that the border of the drag&drop-boxes  used  for  the  icons  to  be
dropped over FreshIconizer are the same as these used for textboxes.

The GUI constists of 3  windows:  The  mainwindow,  an  aboutwindow  and  a
settingswindow.

I tried to hold the mainwindow as small as possible to use only little space
on your Workbench. The minimum-size of the drag&drop-boxes are the default-
size of the FreshIcons.

FreshIconizer supports the bubble-help of MUI. Move your mousepointer  over
the  element  you  want  help  for  and  wait a bit (a few seconds). To use
bubble-help, MUI-3.x or better is required.

FreshIconizer  V1.21:
· was  compiled with SAS/C  V6.56,
· needs MUI 3.x (bubble-help)
· supports the locale.library,
· has NO ARexxPort.

@endnode
/*E*/
/*S*/ Bedienung
@node "Usage" "FreshIconizer - Usage"
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{b}@{u}4. Usage@{uu}@{ub}@{FG TEXT}

@{i}Here is explained how to use FreshIconizer.@{ui}

After you started FreshIconizer a window is opened containing 2 boxes and 3
gadgets.

@{FG FILL}The Icon-Dropboxes@{FG TEXT}
The  two  boxes  are  so-called  "@{b}Icon-Dropboxes@{ub}".  With  them   you   tell
FreshIconizer  what  is  the  source-  and what is the destination-icon. To
state which is the sourceicon, you just drag the wanted icon over the  left
box  and drop it there. FreshIconizer thereupon loads the icon and shows it
in this box. As you might think the right box is for the  destination-icon.
Immediately after dropping the destination-object it is modified in the way
you set in the prefswindow and is saved again. It's also possible  to  drop
more than one icon at the same time because multiselect is supported.

If you click with your mouse into an Icon-Dropbox the  selected  icon-image
is shown.

@{FG FILL}The settings@{FG TEXT}
With the 1st gadget "@{b}Settings@{ub}" you open a further window in  wich  you  can
set  the  behavior of FreshIconizer when a destination-icon is dropped. See
also: @{"Settingswindow" LINK "win.prefs"}

@{FG FILL}The Info-Button@{FG TEXT}
In the middle of the gadgets is the "@{b}Info@{ub}"-gadget. A click on  it  opens  a
little  information-window  containing  the  versionnumber, the name of the
author, a dedication, which compiler was used and a copyright  note.  Close
this window with the "@{b}Okay@{ub}" button.

@{FG FILL}Leaving the program@{FG TEXT}
The last gadget "@{b}Quit@{ub}" serves, as the name already  says,  the  leaving  of
FreshIconizer.  It's  also  possible to quit it by using the closegadget of
the mainwindow. Any window of FreshIconizer still opened will be closed.  A
further way to quit FreshIconizer is to use the Exchange-program. Choose it
in its list of Commodities and press the "@{b}Remove@{ub}"-gadget.
@endnode
/*E*/
/*S*/ Einstellungen
@NODE "win.prefs" "FreshIconizer - The Settings"
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{b}@{u}4.1 The Settingswindow@{uu}@{ub}@{FG TEXT}

@{i}Now read this to get informations on how to use the settingswindow.@{ui}

In the settingswindow you can set, which parameters of  an  icon  shall  be
modified  in  which way The destinationicon will have this parameters then.
These are the parameters:

@{FG FILL}Iconimages@{FG TEXT}
Via a cycle-gadget you set whether the imagedata  of  the  icons  shall  be
taken over either from the source-icon or it shall be kept.

@{FG FILL}Icontypes@{FG TEXT}
With this parameter you set, which type the destination-icon is to  be  of.
There  are  3  choices:  1st, to keep the icontype of the destination-icon;
2nd, to convert the type to the same type as the source-icon; and the  3rd,
to force one of the existing icontypes (e.g. Disk, Drawer, Tool...)

@{FG FILL}Tooltypes@{FG TEXT}
For the tooltypes you have similar choices: You can choose either  to  keep
the tooltypes or to take over the source-icon's tooltypes.

@{FG FILL}Position of the icons@{FG TEXT}
The position of the destination-icon can be kept or be taken over from  the
source-icon. Further it's possible to free the position of the icon.

@{FG FILL}Defaulttool@{FG TEXT}
This parameter is not used for every kind of icon, instead only for disk-
and project-icons. It holds the name of program to run if:

1. A diskicon is dropped over an other.
2. A project is opened (doubleclicked)

The program is given the drivename/filename as argument. A textfile  should
have  the name of a editor or so as defaulttool. To set this defaulttool in
the destination-icon you can either take over it from the source-icon, keep
the defaultool or set this information explicitly. For the last, some often
used tools are predefined in a list, but you can  also  set  a  userdefined
tool by choosing it through a filerequester.

@{FG FILL}Stacksize@{FG TEXT}
Also this parameter is not relevant for all icontypes.  This  is  only  for
tool-  and  projecticons. It represents the size of the stackmemory used by
the tool or by the defaulttool of the projecticon. If you  aren't  familiar
with   such  things,  let  it  as  it  is  (keep  the  size  given  in  the
destination-icon).. Otherwise you have the choice between taking over  from
source, keeping it or setting the size explicitly.


@{i}To take over all these settings there are the following ways:@{ui}
· Using  the  @{b}close-symbol@{ub} of the window: Take over parameters and use them
  until you quit the program or change them again.
· Pressing the @{b}Okay-button@{ub}: Parameter-takeover and use of them until reboot
  or changing of them.
· Pressing the @{b}Save-button@{ub}: With  that  the settings are fixed  permanently
  until you change them again.
· @{b}Cancel@{ub}: This lets you leave  the settings window without any takeover  of
  your changed settings.
@ENDNODE
